<div1 type="letter">

<pb facs="nei.j4a.2.30-32_0001b" />

<opener>
<dateline>June 23- 1912</dateline>

<fw type="letterhead">Pendennis Club</fw>


<salute>My dear Neihardt: &#8212;</salute></opener> <p>I should be delighted to have a copy of your last vol., "The Stranger at the Gate," reviews of which I have been reading with interest. If it is as good as your "Man Song" I shall be 

<fw type="curatorial">30</fw>

<pb facs="nei.j4a.2.30-32_0002b"/>   

satisfied.</p>

<p>I am sending you another little book of mine, now out of print, entitled "Myth and Romance". I have checked in the table of contents the poems I think most worthy of your consideration. I happened to find this extra copy on my shelves, and am

<fw type="curatorial">31</fw>
   
   <pb facs="nei.j4a.2.30-32_0002a"/>

glad to make you a present of it.</p>

<p>Yes; we are certainly living in a great lyrical age, but the readers of books don't or won't recognize it. As for <hi rend="underline">Sterling</hi> I admire his work greatly; but would admire it more if he were more simple. He keeps his head constantly among

<pb facs="nei.j4a.2.30-32_0001a"/>

<note type="curatorial">200 Neihardt Collection</note>

the stars and seldom condescends to come down from the heights to good old mother Earth.</p>

<p>Good luck and good health to you.</p>
<closer>
<salute>Your friend,</salute>

<signed>Madison Cawein</signed>
</closer>

<note type="curatorial">In <title><hi rend="underline">The Vale of Tempe</hi></title> &#8212; Madison Cawein</note>

